</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="97" pageNumber="97" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="97.[128,654,213,1759]" pageId="97" pageNumber="97">REMARKS: This species, the smallest known from the New World, has a robust abdomen, the pronotal length is marginally shorter than the width, and the lateroapical processes of tergum IX are far longer than in other species and are so strongly bent that they nearly form a semicircle. The male is not known, but it is expected that the lateroapical processes of tergum IX would be similarly long and strongly curved. The lateroapical processes are narrowly separated prior to dissection and nearly touch each other for almost their entire length.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
